  <h2>Complex Compensation Issues in Professional Divorce</h2>

  <h3>Stock Options, RSUs, and Equity Compensation</h3>
  <p>
    Executive compensation packages often include stock options, restricted stock units (RSUs), performance shares, and deferred compensation. Determining which of these are marital property — and how to value and divide them — requires specialized knowledge. Vesting schedules, grant dates, and tax implications all affect the analysis.
  </p>

  <h3>Partnership Interests</h3>
  <p>
    Professional partnerships in law firms, medical groups, accounting firms, and similar entities involve complex ownership structures. Partnership agreements, buy-sell clauses, and capital accounts all factor into the division analysis. Our attorneys are experienced in handling partnership interest valuation and division.
  </p>

  <h3>Deferred Compensation and Bonuses</h3>
  <p>
    Bonuses, profit-sharing arrangements, and deferred compensation earned during the marriage may be subject to equitable distribution even if paid after the divorce. Proper accounting for these items is essential to a fair outcome.
  </p>

  <h3>Professional Licenses and Degrees</h3>
  <p>
    While professional licenses themselves are generally not divisible marital property, the <em>enhanced earning capacity</em> they generate may be relevant to alimony and support calculations. Maryland courts consider the respective earning capacities of both parties in making support determinations.
  </p>

  <h2>Protecting Your Professional Practice</h2>
  <p>
    If you own or hold an interest in a professional practice — a medical group, law firm, dental practice, or consulting firm — its valuation and division requires specialized expertise. We work with certified business valuators and forensic accountants who specialize in professional practice valuation, including the critical distinction between personal and enterprise goodwill.
  </p>

  <h2>Child Custody for Busy Professionals</h2>
  <p>
    Professionals with demanding schedules face unique custody considerations. Long hours, travel requirements, on-call responsibilities, and irregular schedules must be carefully integrated into parenting plans. Our attorneys craft custody and visitation arrangements that are realistic for your professional life while genuinely serving your children's best interests.
  </p>

  <h2>Spousal Support Considerations for High Earners</h2>
  <p>
    High-earning professionals often face significant alimony exposure in divorce. Our attorneys conduct thorough analysis of Maryland's alimony factors — including each party's financial needs, ability to pay, standard of living during the marriage, and duration — and develop strategic positions that protect your financial interests.
  </p>

